latestPosts.caption:
Hello everyone!! I’m Irene, a mom-of-two that is a part-time night owl because I teach English online to kiddos on the other side of the earth! I also enjoy content creating on @bossbabykiki and created @pnw_moms to bring moms, small business owners and other content creators together in the PNW area! I love seeing the events, experiences and creativity everyone has to offer and hope to continue to support moms in any way I possibly can here!

Just like many, I am a PNW transplant and moved to Seattle from Singapore in 2011! I lived in Singapore for five years and got my bachelors in Communications, hence my passion for social media and content creating! Before Singapore, I was in Burma, which is where I was born, but spent a good deal of my childhood in Sydney, Australia (9 years) before moving back to Burma. I think I’ve packed and moved my life multiple times and honestly am just thankful to have settled down! Fast forward, I met my husband in Seattle in 2014 and we decided to move down to Eastern WA after the birth of our second kiddo. 

After living in big cities for so long, I never expected to love being in the countryside! But I do! I love the peace and quiet, abundant of space, being close to nature, and the feeling of living each day at a slower pace! It has really improved my anxiety and stress which can take quite a toll on me. My favorite things are hiking 🥾, long walks to the fridge/ pantry 🤪, eating spicy food, like really spicy🌶️, coffee ☕️ and lately gardening 👩🏻‍🌾, or trying to! So glad to have met you all here! 🫶🏼

Happy Happy Friday!!

🚂💭 “Is this a movie set?”
Nope—just a real-life Time Machine hiding in plain sight at the Northwest Railway Museum, Snoqualmie Depot.

Step onto the platform and you’re instantly whisked back to the golden age of railroads—steam engines, vintage railcars, and that unmistakable choo choo echoing through the Cascades. 🏔️✨

🛤️ Northwest Railway Museum is more than a photo-worthy pit stop—it’s a living, breathing piece of history. It’s your gateway to a 2-hour scenic train ride with panoramic views of the Cascade foothills, Snoqualmie Falls, and charming small towns.

🛤️ Ride in historic railcars and feel the rhythm of the rails as you chug along between Snoqualmie, North Bend, and the Railway History Campus.

🎟️ Tickets:
👶 Kids (2–12): $12
👩‍🦱 Adults (13–61): $28
👵 Seniors (62+): $24
🎫 Infants ride free!

✨ Admission includes train ride(Either from Snoqualmie or North Bend Depot) + access to the Train Shed Exhibit Hall—packed with restored locomotives and hands-on displays!

🚨 Pro tip: Combine it with a waterfall stop or a café crawl in downtown or a splash pad at Snoqualmie community park for a dreamy and sunny PNW day.

📅 P.S. Their seasonal rides (like Day Out With Thomas or Wine train excursion) sell out fast! You’ll want to hop aboard early.

Covington, Washington is one of South King County’s blossoming cities, with so much to offer! They provide year-round events, with activities really ramping up in the warmer months. The summer park pop-ups are always free with something new for kids to enjoy! This week was a splash park and there was already a Superhero Meet & Greet, and Ready, Set, Play kick-off: where kids can earn “brag tags” while visiting local businesses.

Questions about Covington or setting up a home search here? Send me a DM or comment below! 🏡

————

Covington is a great place to live, work, shop and play! Covington is located in King County close to the Puget Sound with views of Mount Rainier. As a young city, incorporated in 1997, Covington is proud of its family-oriented, small-town character and diverse commercial opportunities. Covington is committed to being a city where the residents, businesses and civic leaders partner together to maintain a strong sense of peace and community.

🍓 Strawberry Festival on Vashon Island is happening July 18th-20th and it’s one of the best family-friendly events of the summer!

There’s a big parade, tons of activities for kids, live music, delicious food, and that small-town magic that makes it feel like a true summer celebration.

If you’re planning to go (or thinking about it!), this reel has 7 family-friendly things to do while you’re on the island, from playgrounds to peaceful beaches and fun food stops. It’s the perfect way to round out your visit! 👇🏼

	1.	🛝 Dockton Park playground
	2.	🐦 Visit Oscar the Bird King
	3.	☕ Coffee stop at @vashon_island_coffee_roasterie 
	4.	🍔 Lunch @vashonislandqueen 
	5.	🏖 Explore Point Robinson (beach + lighthouse + troll!)
	6.	🚣 Paddle or play near Quartermaster Harbor. Rent kayaks or paddleboards @vashonadventures 
	7.	🍏 Sip & roam at @dragonsheadcider (kids are welcome at the Orchard location)

It’s an easy day trip that feels like a mini vacation — save this for your next island adventure!
	
Just a short ferry ride from West Seattle or Tacoma, Vashon makes for an easy, fun summer day trip with kids. Festival or not.
Save this for your trip! 🛳️✨

Sunrise views worth the early wake-up call! 🏔️✨

Planning a summer trip to Mount Rainier’s Sunrise Corridor? Here’s what you need to know 👇

🚘 Timed Entry starts July 11 – required 7 AM–5 PM
🎟️ Reserve your slot on Recreation.gov ($2 + park entry)
⏰ No reservation needed if you enter before 7 AM or after 5 PM
🎟️Additional slots become available at 7 PM the day before your visit.

👧 Kid-friendly trails to try:
🌲 Sunrise Nature Trail – 1.5 mi loop
🌼 Silver Forest Trail – 2 mi with Mountain View’s
Frozen Lake Trail - 3 mi loop via sourdough ridge
🌸 Emmons Vista – .5 mi loop short & sweet!
🌸 Tipsoo Lake trail - .5 mi walk around the lake

✅ Pro tip: Book early, pack snacks, and don’t forget your park pass! Weather changes constantly so be prepared.

Waterfalls you can walk behind? Yes, please! 💧🌲

Silver Falls State Park is an Oregon classic just 80 minutes from Portland, featuring the stunning Trail of Ten Falls — a 7.4-mile loop through mossy forests, misty falls, and fairy-tale vibes.

✨ Short on time or hiking with kids?

You can hike a scenic 2-mile stretch from South Falls to North Falls via the Canyon Trail — just be sure to arrange a shuttle or park a second car at the North Falls trailhead for a one-way trip.

Alternatively, you can park at each trailhead and enjoy the short hikes individually :
- South Falls via Canyon Trail: Just 0.8 miles roundtrip — and you get to walk behind the iconic curtain of water!

- North Falls Viewpoint: A quick 0.6 miles roundtrip from the North Fall parking lot — with serious wow factor.

👟 Trail difficulty: Easy to moderate
🚗 Parking: $10/day or valid Oregon State Parks Pass

This park is proof you don’t need a long hike for big beauty — just bring your camera, a rain jacket, snacks and sense of wonder. 💚

👟 Pro tip: Arrive early on weekends, parking lots get full. Also carry rain jackets.

💬 Tell us your favorite waterfall in the comments — we’re always chasing new ones!
